82    /**
83    * jEdit's text area component. It is more suited for editing program source code than JEditorPane,
84    * because it drops the unnecessary features (images, variable-width lines, and so on) and adds a
85    * whole bunch of useful goodies such as:
86    * <ul>
87    * <li>More flexible key binding scheme
88    * <li>Supports macro recorders
89    * <li>Rectangular selection
90    * <li>Bracket highlighting
91    * <li>Syntax highlighting
92    * <li>Command repetition
93    * <li>Block caret can be enabled
94    * </ul>
95    * It is also faster and doesn't have as many problems. It can be used in other applications; the
96    * only other part of jEdit it depends on is the syntax package.
97    * <p>
98    *
99    * To use it in your app, treat it like any other component, for example:
100    *
101    * <pre>
102    * JEditTextArea ta = new JEditTextArea();
103    * ta.setTokenMarker(new JavaTokenMarker());
104    * ta.setText(&quot;public class Test {&quot; + &quot;
105    * public static void main(String[] args) {&quot; + &quot;
106    * System.out.println(\&quot;Hello World\&quot;);&quot; + &quot;
107    * }&quot; + &quot;}&quot;);
108    * </pre>
109    *
110    * @author Slava Pestov, Ingo Mierswa, Tobias Malbrecht
111    */
